A young man named Arjun often complained, "My mind is useless. It keeps thinking about things that don't matter."
His thoughts jumped everywhere past mistakes, future worries, and small problems that grew bigger in his head.
One day, he visited an old teacher and said, "I wish my mind would just stop."
The teacher handed him a small cup filled with muddy water and said, "Hold this."
Arjun held the cup while the teacher said nothing. After a few minutes, the mud slowly settled at the bottom, and water became clear.
"Did you clean it?" the teacher asked.
"No," Arjun replied. "I just waited."
The teacher smiled.
"Your mind is the same. It is not useless. It is just restless. When you stop fighing it and give it stillness, it becomes clear."
From that day, Arjun stopped calling his mind useless.
Instead, he learned how to quiet it.
And in that quiet, he found peace.
